{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"37"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/37"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.12,0.08,0.16,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"37"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59141"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/37"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"37"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2899"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43778"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59141"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of dysphagia to solids and fluids. She has lost 4 kg in weight over this time. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as a store clerk involving heavy manual labour. She reports stiffness in her hands which she attributes to arthritis. For many years, her fingers turn blue in cold weather, improving with warming. She denies fever, rash, reflux, change in bowel habit, abdominal pain or chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and SpO2 96% on room air. Her chest is clear on auscultation. Her hands are as shown (Image). There is puckering around her mouth. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following autoantibodies is most specific for this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-U1 ribonucleoprotein","Anti-Jo-1","Anti-La","Anti-nuclear antibody","Anti-centromere"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of limited systemic sclerosis (formerly known as CREST syndrome), including Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, sclerodactyly, and oesophageal dysmotility. The diagnosis is supported by the characteristic perioral puckering.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-centromere\u003C/strong\u003E antibodies are highly specific (95%) for limited systemic sclerosis and are present in 82-96% of patients. They are valuable for both diagnosis and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-U1 ribonucleoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E antibodies are characteristic of mixed connective tissue disease, which can have overlapping features with systemic sclerosis but typically includes features of systemic lupus erythematosus and polymyositis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-Jo-1\u003C/strong\u003E antibodies are associated with polymyositis and dermatomyositis, particularly in patients with interstitial lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-La\u003C/strong\u003E antibodies, along with anti-Ro antibodies, are characteristic of Sj\u00f6gren\u0027s syndrome, which can cause dryness but not the skin changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-nuclear antibody\u003C/strong\u003E testing is sensitive but not specific for systemic sclerosis, as it can be positive in many autoimmune conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELimited systemic sclerosis (CREST) is characterised by Calcinosis, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, oEsophageal dysmotility, Sclerodactyly, and Telangiectasia. This differs from diffuse systemic sclerosis, which involves more extensive skin involvement and internal organ manifestations, and is associated with anti-Scl-70 antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-centromere antibodies are highly specific (95%) for limited systemic sclerosis","The combination of Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, sclerodactyly and oesophageal dysmotility suggests systemic sclerosis","Limited systemic sclerosis (CREST) is characterised by calcinosis, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, oesophageal dysmotility, sclerodactyly and telangiectasia"],"references":["Gabrielli A, Avvedimento EV, Krieg T. Scleroderma. N Engl J Med. 2009; 360:1989-2003."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"37"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17471"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17471"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bee92452-4cdb-4f09-bc60-2a419b72161f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bee92452-4cdb-4f09-bc60-2a419b72161f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T09:38:03+10:30",